We should make the billing guide mandatory where it adds value. Partners sometimes resist, but if it reduces back-and-forth and errors, it should be enforced. Billing guides and engagement letters should be stored centrally. When partners print a pro forma or draft invoice, that should pull data from the billing guide and 3E. Some fields—like currency—are often manually changed in error; ideally, the correct billing currency is set in the billing guide.

Regarding write-offs and client-level decisions: some actions (for example, writing off travel time or small items) may be agreed locally and applied to the client. Those scenarios can vary. We should capture them and, where possible, automate or formalise the process in ServiceNow.

I’ve started a list of discussion points and action items. We should map the main activities that come from a pro forma and follow the natural progression. Marwan and the WIP team are on this call—these are the processes for WIP that we can examine. Examples include time transfers (often retrospective), credit notes, cancellations, and reversals.

Cancellations are usually post-issue: partners sometimes decide to cancel an invoice after it’s been generated. We need to differentiate cancellations and reversals in the system. A cancellation might simply be putting an invoice back into WIP; a reversal is an accounting reversal of the invoice. We need to capture these statuses clearly so we can track actions and metrics (e.g., return to WIP, rework, close complete).

When an invoice is cancelled or reversed, we want the ServiceNow ticket to reflect that. For example, if an invoice is reversed and returned to WIP, the billing team should close their part of the ticket and WIP should pick it up. That way, you won’t keep getting a new ticket each time; instead, the workflow status changes.

On reversals and status changes: many of these activities are performed in 3E, not ServiceNow. But ServiceNow could have alerts or checkpoints—closing a ticket in ServiceNow could trigger checks in 3E or at least show status updates to billing. We discussed how to ensure credit control and other stakeholders are copied or alerted on key status changes.

WIP management activities and amendments often come from the WIP team. They have their own category and team that handle fee earner queries. We should capture the outcomes of these activities (e.g., what was billed, what was written off) and create a consistent way to record them. A simple manual entry showing the work completed and outcomes would help to track recurring themes and justify resourcing or training.

Scheduled activities: some of the team’s tasks are calendared (e.g., weekly updates). We could capture those scheduled activities in ServiceNow for metrics—for example, time taken to resolve ad-hoc items or scheduled reconciliation tasks. Over time, these metrics will demonstrate workload and capacity issues across billing and support arguments for resource changes.

On the intake form: instead of free text, require key fields. Make mandatory fields to reduce the need to chase for basic data. Auto-assign and categorise tickets so that work is evenly distributed. Allow reassignments across the team and make visibility of queues clear. Consider priority flags for urgent items, but keep the form simple; don’t overcomplicate it with too many conditional rules at the start.

Urgency is subjective, so define clear prioritisation rules—e.g., administrative tasks versus time-sensitive matters like insolvency or company administration. Use the form to capture reasons for high priority and then ServiceNow can prioritise based on those fields.

We should produce user stories and map scenarios. Capture the common queries and reversals, the typical reasons for them (e.g., rate changes, negotiated discounts, volume discounts), and incorporate them into the intake options. Some situations will require bespoke handling, but many will fit standard patterns.

