On pro formas: a pro forma is not always created before a request lands. Sometimes PEs will ask us to generate a pro forma, and other times they have created one already. For e-billing clients, the client billing requirements are usually captured on the pro forma. The team will check those requirements when processing.

When we generate the pro forma in 3E, any billing guide provided should be attached to the pro forma. That attachment should remain visible and auditable. When an invoice is sent, we typically send a PDF copy back to the PE for their records.

Checks we perform during processing include: verifying client name, address, VAT details, client ID, country, tax treatment, and other regulatory items. Some checks are automated in 3E, but we often need to sense-check data that doesn't map correctly. We should formalise a short checklist in the ServiceNow ticket to capture the key checks performed by billing before closing the ticket.

Approvals: there aren’t many formal approvals in the billing flow, but queries on rates, addresses, or other billing guide details result in back-and-forth. If cases are part-paid or disputed, the billing team will handle those in collaboration with credit control.

When the invoice is generated in 3E, we send the PDF to the PE. For e-billing clients, the invoice goes to the client portal. We should record that the invoice has been issued and provide a thumbnail or attachment in ServiceNow for the requester’s information.

Common scenarios to map:
- Cancellations and reversals (differentiate the two)
- Invoice reissue (often handled as a new invoice request once the original is closed)
- Time transfers and merging time cards (pre- or post-billing)
- Splitting bills between matters or clients (co-client splits)
- Write-offs and credit accounts (different terminology used by different teams)
- Retainer invoices and money on account
- Sundry invoices (non-client, office expenses like seminar fees)
- Complex client groups (Goldman Sachs, Citigroup, JP Morgan) that have structured, high-volume processes and tight workflows

Splitting bills: requests come from PEs or PAs and must include matter numbers and the basis of the split (percentages or amounts). We should require the matter number(s) and specify whether it’s a co-client split or another scenario. Validating matter numbers at intake can reduce errors.

Write-offs and credit accounts: there’s confusion over terminology (credit account vs. value account). We should standardise the language in the intake form so the PE selects from defined options (e.g., write-off, credit account allocation) and provides the amount and any approval evidence. That gives a clear audit trail.

Handling scribbled PDFs and manual annotation: partners and PEs sometimes submit hand-marked PDFs with highlights and hand notes. That leads to errors. The intake should provide a structured form where they can specify exact line items, time entries, or amounts to write off or amend. Capture the details in a consistent format rather than relying on annotated attachments.

Complex billing: there are client-specific processes for large clients like Goldman Sachs, Citi, and JP Morgan. These are often run by specific people and include scheduled reports, bulk files, and client portal interactions. Rejections from client portals occur frequently; we need a workflow to capture, triage, and process rejected lines—ideally integrated with the client portals and ServiceNow for traceability.

Goldman Sachs and other large clients have a tight, structured workflow. Often email communications and ad-hoc reports are used today; these should be moved into ServiceNow to give visibility (so if someone is out, others can see the status and communications). For bulk file submissions, the workflow must support batch handling and line-item rejections.

E-billing rejections: e-billing portals will reject invoices for various reasons. We need a process to receive those rejections (either via portal integrations or standardised emails) and then issue tickets in ServiceNow to manage remediation and re-submission. Capturing examples of portal rejections will help define the workflow.

Investment funds and APFA processes: some investment fund billing tasks are currently handled by the PF/PA or PFA role. These activities may remain with the billing team but they are scheduled tasks. We should confirm whether these are still required and capture them as scheduled processes or automated reports where appropriate.

Retainers and money on account: these are infrequent but necessary categories. We should keep categories for them and ensure the intake form captures the purpose and GL code if relevant.

Sundry invoices: these are non-client invoices (e.g., internal seminar charges or office expenses). These should be directed to the appropriate AP/GL code and be handled as non-client billing, not client invoicing.

